And these things concerning the prize hoped for, con- cerning the manner in which it respects us in the present life, and also concerning the place where it is lodged. It remains that we say something of that interpretation of Chrysostom and Theodoret, which we adverted to above.

These words, for the hope laid upforyou in heaven, Chry- sostom refers to the love and faith of the Colossians3 as though he would say, Ye have believed, and have exer- cised love towards the brethren on account of the hope laid up for you in heaven, i. e. on account of the reward of celestial blessedness. It is necessary to say something concerning this interpretation, inasmuch as the words bear it, and many interpreters follow it.
